  "prompt": "How does international law intersect with national laws on money laundering?",
  "response": "International law intersects with national laws on money laundering through several key mechanisms:\n\n1. International Frameworks and Conventions\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Basel Committee guidelines\n- Egmont Group of Financial Intelligence Units\n\n2. Legal Coordination Mechanisms\n- Mutual legal assistance treaties\n- Extradition agreements\n- Information sharing protocols\n- Cross-border investigation collaboration\n\n3. Standardized Regulatory Requirements\n- Know Your Customer (KYC) regulations\n- Suspicious transaction reporting\n- Customer due diligence standards\n- Asset tracking and freezing procedures\n\n4. Enforcement Approaches\n- Coordinated international investigations\n- Shared intelligence databases\n- Consistent legal definitions of money laundering\n- Harmonized prosecution standards\n\n5. Compliance Mechanisms\n- Global banking compliance standards\n- Uniform reporting requirements\n- Transnational financial monitoring\n- Sanctions for non-compliance\n\nThese intersections create a complex, multi-layered system of legal cooperation aimed at preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities across national boundaries.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any of these specific aspects of international money laundering law?",
